{
  "What type of growth occurs when a population increases by a constant proportion in each generation with unlimited resources?": "",
  "Logistic growth": "",
  "Arithmetic growth": "",
  "Linear growth": "",
  "Exponential growth": "",
  "Exponential growth describes a population that multiplies by a constant factor each generation, producing a J-shaped curve. This occurs when resources are unlimited and there are no environmental constraints on reproduction.": "",
  "Which curve shape is characteristic of logistic population growth?": "",
  "U-shaped curve": "",
  "S-shaped curve": "",
  "J-shaped curve": "",
  "V-shaped curve": "",
  "Logistic growth produces an S-shaped (sigmoid) curve because the population grows rapidly at first, then slows as it approaches the carrying capacity. The S-shape reflects increasing environmental resistance as the population grows.": "",
  "What is the carrying capacity of an environment?": "",
  "The rate at which a population can grow": "",
  "The total number of species an ecosystem can hold": "",
  "The minimum population size needed for survival": "",
  "The maximum population size an environment can sustain indefinitely": "",
  "Carrying capacity (K) is the largest population size that an environment can support indefinitely given available resources such as food, water, and space. When a population reaches K, birth and death rates are roughly equal.": "",
  "Which of the following is an example of a density-dependent factor?": "",
  "A volcanic eruption": "",
  "A hurricane": "",
  "Competition for food": "",
  "A wildfire": "",
  "Density-dependent factors, such as competition for food, become more intense as population density increases. Unlike density-independent factors like natural disasters, their impact scales with the number of individuals in a given area.": "",
  "In the logistic growth equation dN/dt = rN((K − N)/K), what does 'r' represent?": "",
  "Carrying capacity": "",
  "Reproduction interval": "",
  "Current population size": "",
  "Intrinsic rate of natural increase": "",
  "In the logistic equation, 'r' stands for the intrinsic rate of natural increase, which is the maximum per-capita growth rate when resources are unlimited. It reflects the difference between birth and death rates under ideal conditions.": "",
  "Which survivorship curve describes species that experience high mortality early in life but high survival rates once they reach adulthood?": "",
  "Type I": "",
  "Type II": "",
  "Type III": "",
  "Type IV": "",
  "Type III survivorship curves are found in species like marine fish and sea turtles that produce many offspring but provide little parental care. Most individuals die young, but those that survive to adulthood have much higher survival rates.": "",
  "Which organisms are most likely to be K-selected species?": "",
  "Phytoplankton species": "",
  "Whales and dolphins": "",
  "Bacteria in a tidal pool": "",
  "Annual algae blooms": "",
  "K-selected species like whales and dolphins are characterized by long lifespans, few offspring, and extensive parental care. They tend to live near the carrying capacity of their environment and invest heavily in each individual offspring.": "",
  "What happens to population growth rate as a population nears its carrying capacity in logistic growth?": "",
  "It slows and approaches zero": "",
  "It increases exponentially": "",
  "It remains constant": "",
  "It fluctuates randomly": "",
  "As a population nears carrying capacity, resources become scarce and competition intensifies, causing the growth rate to decline toward zero. At K, births roughly equal deaths and net population change is approximately zero.": "",
  "In the mark-recapture method, what assumption must be true for accurate population estimates?": "",
  "The population must be growing exponentially": "",
  "All individuals must be recaptured": "",
  "Marked individuals must leave the population": "",
  "Marked and unmarked individuals must mix randomly": "",
  "The mark-recapture (Lincoln-Petersen) method assumes that marked individuals mix randomly back into the population before the second sample. If mixing is not random, the proportion of marked individuals in the recapture will be biased.": "",
  "Which of the following best describes the Lotka-Volterra predator-prey model?": "",
  "Prey populations always increase while predator populations decrease": "",
  "Predator and prey populations remain stable at all times": "",
  "Predator and prey populations oscillate in linked cycles": "",
  "Both populations grow exponentially without limit": "",
  "The Lotka-Volterra model predicts that predator and prey populations undergo coupled oscillations. As prey increase, predators have more food and also increase; the rising predator numbers then reduce prey, which subsequently causes predator numbers to fall.": "",
  "What term describes the maximum per-capita rate of increase of a population under ideal conditions?": "",
  "Net reproductive rate": "",
  "Ecological footprint": "",
  "Biotic potential": "",
  "Biotic potential refers to the maximum reproductive capacity of a population under optimal environmental conditions with unlimited resources. It represents the fastest possible rate of increase and is rarely achieved in natural settings due to environmental resistance.": "",
  "What does the term 'environmental resistance' refer to in population ecology?": "",
  "The collective factors that limit population growth": "",
  "An organism's immune system fighting disease": "",
  "The ability of a species to adapt to climate change": "",
  "The physical barriers that separate habitats": "",
  "Environmental resistance is the sum of all biotic and abiotic factors—such as predation, disease, competition, and limited resources—that prevent a population from growing at its biotic potential. It is the reason populations follow logistic rather than exponential growth.": "",
  "Which term describes species that reproduce rapidly, mature early, and produce many offspring with little parental care?": "",
  "K-selected species": "",
  "Keystone species": "",
  "r-selected species": "",
  "Apex predators": "",
  "r-selected species invest energy in producing large numbers of offspring rather than in parental care. They tend to colonize unstable or unpredictable environments and rely on sheer numbers rather than individual survivorship.": "",
  "What is 'maximum sustainable yield' (MSY) in fisheries management?": "",
  "The largest catch that can be taken indefinitely without depleting the stock": "",
  "The average weight of fish harvested per year": "",
  "The total biomass of fish in the ocean at any time": "",
  "The minimum number of fish needed to prevent extinction": "",
  "Maximum sustainable yield is the greatest number of individuals that can be harvested from a population on an ongoing basis without causing the population to decline. It is theoretically achieved when the population is at roughly half its carrying capacity, where growth rate is highest.": "",
  "What does the variable 'K' represent in the logistic growth model?": "",
  "The initial population size": "",
  "The death rate": "",
  "The carrying capacity": "",
  "The intrinsic growth rate": "",
  "In the logistic growth equation, K stands for carrying capacity—the maximum number of individuals the environment can support long-term. As N approaches K, the term (K − N)/K approaches zero, slowing growth.": "",
  "Which term describes a graph that plots the proportion of a cohort still alive at each age?": "",
  "Growth rate chart": "",
  "Age-structure diagram": "",
  "Population pyramid": "",
  "Survivorship curve": "",
  "A survivorship curve plots the number or proportion of individuals surviving to each age in a cohort. The three classic types (I, II, III) differ in when most mortality occurs and reflect different life-history strategies.": "",
  "What is the Lincoln-Petersen index used to estimate?": "",
  "Species diversity in a community": "",
  "Population size using mark-recapture data": "",
  "The growth rate of a population": "",
  "The effect of predation on prey abundance": "",
  "The Lincoln-Petersen index (N = MC/R) uses the ratio of marked to unmarked individuals in a recapture sample to estimate total population size. It is one of the most widely used formulas in wildlife and fisheries biology.": "",
  "Which vocabulary term describes factors whose impact on a population does NOT change with population density?": "",
  "Biotic factors": "",
  "Regulatory factors": "",
  "Density-independent factors": "",
  "Density-dependent factors": "",
  "Density-independent factors, such as floods, droughts, and extreme temperatures, affect populations regardless of their size or density. They can cause sudden population crashes that are not related to how crowded the population is.": "",
  "What does the term 'cohort' mean in the context of population ecology?": "",
  "A group of different species living together": "",
  "The dominant predator in a food web": "",
  "A group of individuals born at approximately the same time": "",
  "A measure of genetic diversity within a population": "",
  "A cohort is a group of individuals of the same species that are born at roughly the same time. Tracking a cohort through time allows ecologists to construct life tables and survivorship curves that describe mortality patterns.": "",
  "What is the term for the phenomenon in which predator population peaks lag behind prey population peaks?": "",
  "Density-dependent feedback": "",
  "Phase-shifted oscillation": "",
  "Trophic cascade": "",
  "Competitive exclusion": "",
  "In Lotka-Volterra dynamics, predator population peaks are phase-shifted—they follow prey peaks after a time lag because predator reproduction depends on prey availability. This offset produces the characteristic cycling pattern observed in many predator-prey systems.": "",
  "A marine biologist tags 200 sea bass in a bay. Two weeks later, she captures 150 sea bass and finds that 30 of them are tagged. Using the Lincoln-Petersen method, what is the estimated population size?": "",
  "1,000": "",
  "500": "",
  "1,500": "",
  "750": "",
  "Using N = MC/R: N = (200 × 150)/30 = 1,000. The proportion of marked fish in the recapture sample (30/150 = 0.20) is assumed to reflect the proportion of marked fish in the total population (200/1,000 = 0.20).": "",
  "A coral reef fish population has a carrying capacity of 10,000 and is currently at 2,000 individuals with r = 0.5. Using the logistic model, approximately what is the population growth rate (dN/dt)?": "",
  "500 individuals per unit time": "",
  "400 individuals per unit time": "",
  "800 individuals per unit time": "",
  "1,000 individuals per unit time": "",
  "Using dN/dt = rN((K − N)/K): 0.5 × 2,000 × ((10,000 − 2,000)/10,000) = 0.5 × 2,000 × 0.8 = 800. The population is well below K, so the (K − N)/K term is large, allowing relatively fast growth.": "",
  "An island population of seabirds suddenly crashes after a severe hurricane, regardless of the colony size. This is best explained by which type of factor?": "",
  "Density-independent factor": "",
  "Interspecific competition": "",
  "K-selection pressure": "",
  "Density-dependent factor": "",
  "A hurricane kills organisms regardless of how many are present, making it a density-independent factor. Density-independent factors affect the same proportion of a population no matter how large or crowded it is.": "",
  "A fisheries manager determines that a tuna stock with a carrying capacity of 50,000 is currently at 25,000 fish. Why is this population level significant for harvest management?": "",
  "The population is at maximum sustainable yield because growth rate is highest at K/2": "",
  "It indicates the stock is no longer commercially viable": "",
  "It is an endangered population level requiring a total fishing ban": "",
  "The population is above carrying capacity and must be reduced": "",
  "In the logistic model, population growth rate is maximized when N = K/2. At this point, the population can replace the most harvested individuals per unit time, making it the theoretical target for maximum sustainable yield.": "",
  "A researcher studying sea turtles finds that out of 1,000 hatchlings, only 5 survive to adulthood, but those adults live for decades. Which survivorship curve does this species exhibit?": "",
  "A combination of Type I and Type II": "",
  "Sea turtles follow a Type III survivorship curve because the vast majority of offspring die before reaching maturity, while the few survivors enjoy relatively long lifespans. This is characteristic of species that produce many offspring but provide minimal parental care.": "",
  "In a kelp forest, sea urchin populations explode after otters are removed by hunting. The urchins overgraze the kelp, and their own population then crashes. Which population dynamic best explains the urchin crash?": "",
  "Immigration from neighboring ecosystems": "",
  "Density-independent mortality from disease": "",
  "Exponential growth without limit": "",
  "Exceeding carrying capacity and resource depletion": "",
  "When sea urchins overshoot the carrying capacity of the kelp forest, the food supply collapses and the population crashes due to starvation. This is a classic example of density-dependent regulation where overconsumption of resources triggers a population decline.": "",
  "Oysters in an estuary produce millions of larvae each season, most of which perish within days. Compared to a whale population in the same region, which statement is correct?": "",
  "Both species are r-selected": "",
  "Oysters are K-selected and whales are r-selected": "",
  "Both species are K-selected": "",
  "Oysters are r-selected and whales are K-selected": "",
  "Oysters exhibit r-selected traits—high fecundity, small offspring, and little parental investment—while whales are K-selected, producing few calves with extensive parental care and long lifespans. These strategies represent opposite ends of the life-history continuum.": "",
  "A population of reef sharks has been stable at 400 individuals for several years. A marine biologist calculates that r = 0.3 and K = 400. What is the predicted growth rate (dN/dt)?": "",
  "120 individuals per year": "",
  "0 individuals per year": "",
  "400 individuals per year": "",
  "60 individuals per year": "",
  "When N equals K, the logistic equation gives dN/dt = rN((K − N)/K) = 0.3 × 400 × ((400 − 400)/400) = 0. At carrying capacity, births equal deaths and net population growth is zero.": "",
  "In a Lotka-Volterra simulation of a coastal ecosystem, the sardine (prey) population peaks in year 3, and the dolphin (predator) population peaks in year 5. If sardine numbers then drop steeply, what should researchers predict for the dolphin population?": "",
  "Dolphins will continue to increase indefinitely": "",
  "Dolphins will decline after a time lag as food becomes scarce": "",
  "Dolphins will switch to exponential growth": "",
  "Dolphins will remain at their peak permanently": "",
  "In the Lotka-Volterra model, a decline in the prey population leads to reduced food availability for predators, causing their population to decline after a time lag. This phase-shifted decline is a fundamental prediction of coupled predator-prey oscillations.": "",
  "Marine biologists are comparing two fish populations. Population A has 5,000 individuals with K = 10,000 and r = 0.4. Population B has 9,000 individuals with K = 10,000 and r = 0.4. Which population has the higher growth rate and why?": "",
  "Population B, because larger populations always grow faster": "",
  "Population B, because it is closer to carrying capacity": "",
  "Both populations have the same growth rate because r and K are identical": "",
  "Population A, because it is at K/2 where logistic growth rate is maximized": "",
  "Population A is at N = K/2, the inflection point of the logistic curve where growth rate is maximized: dN/dt = 0.4 × 5,000 × 0.5 = 1,000. Population B yields dN/dt = 0.4 × 9,000 × 0.1 = 360. The farther a population is from K/2, the lower its absolute growth rate.": ""
}